<handout xml:id="handout-section-7-4-svd">
  <title>7.4 Singular Value Decomposition</title>

  <page xml:id="p-7-4-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-7-4-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>The Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)</li>
        <li>Applications of the SVD</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Compute the SVD of a rectangular matrix.</li>
        <li><p>
          Use the SVD to:
          <ul>
            <li>construct bases for the four fundamental subspaces,</li>
            <li>construct spectral decompositions.</li>
          </ul></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

     <theorem xml:id="thm-svd">
      <title>Singular Value Decomposition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix with rank <m>r</m>.
          Then <m>A</m> can be written as
        </p>
        <md>
          A = U\Sigma V^T = \begin{bmatrix} \vec u_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec u_m \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp \sigma_2 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\ \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp \sigma_r \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \vec v_1^T \\ \vdots \\ \vec v_n^T \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        <p>where</p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>U</m> is an <m>m\times m</m> orthogonal matrix,</li>
          <li><m>V</m> is an <m>n\times n</m> orthogonal matrix,</li>
          <li>
            <m>\Sigma</m> is an <m>m\times n</m> diagonal matrix with
            diagonal entries <m>\sigma_1,\dots,\sigma_r</m>, where <m>\sigma_1 \geq \sigma_2 \geq \cdots \geq \sigma_r \gt 0</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
        Note that Singular Value Decomposition applies to <em>any matrix</em>, not just symmetric or square matrices.
    </p>


  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-4-example1">
    <title>Example 1: Geometry of a Linear Transformation</title>
    <example xml:id="ex-7-4-ellipse" workspace="true">
      <introduction>
        <p>Consider the the linear transformation <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x</m>, where
        <md>
          A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>.
        Note that <m>A</m> has an orthogonal diagonalization given by  
        <md>A = PDP^T = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
          \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1\\ -1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>.
        Also, note that the orthogonal diagonalization of <m>A</m> satisfies the properties of a Singular Value Decomposition. The parts below investigate how multiplication by <m>A</m> acts on <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> geometrically. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
      <task workspace="3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Can you describe geometrically what multiplication by <m>A</m> does to an arbitrary vector <m>\vec x</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let's see if we can figure out what <m>T</m> does to some nice inputs. 
            </p>
            <p> 
                First, let's see what happens to <m>\vec e_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Note that <md>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Geometrically, we can describe the action of <m>T</m> on this vector by scaling the input by <m>\sqrt{10}</m> and rotating it clockwise by some angle <m>\theta</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, let's see what happens to <m>\vec e_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Note that <md>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Geometrically, we can describe the action of <m>T</m> on this vector by scaling the input by <m>\sqrt{10}</m> and rotating it counterclockwise by that same angle <m>\theta</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, let's see what happens to <m>\vec e_1 + \vec e_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Note that <md>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Geometrically, we can describe the action of <m>T</m> on this vector by scaling the input by <m>2</m> and no rotation.
            </p>
            <p>
                It is very hard to describe what <m>T</m> is doing in general that will match the descriptions we found for just these three inputs.
            </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Instead of determining what <m>A</m> does in one fell swoop, let us investigate what each factor of <m>A =PDP^T</m> does. First, determine what multiplication by <m>P^T</m> does to an arbitrary vector <m>\vec x</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <md>P^T = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \cos\left(45^\circ\right) \amp -\sin\left(45^\circ\right) \\ \sin\left(45^\circ\right) \amp \cos\left(45^\circ\right) \end{bmatrix}</md>. Therefore, multiplication by <m>P^T</m> rotates vectors <m>45^\circ</m> counterclockwise.
            </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Next, determine what multiplication by <m>D</m> does to an arbitrary vector <m>\vec x</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <md>D\vec x = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 4x_1 \\ 2x_2 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Thus, multiplication by <m>D</m> scales the vector in the <m>x_1</m>-direction by <m>4</m> and in the <m>x_2</m>-direction by <m>2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now, determine what multiplication by <m>P</m> does to an arbitrary vector <m>\vec x</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <md>P = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \cos\left(-45^\circ\right) \amp -\sin\left(-45^\circ\right) \\ \sin\left(-45^\circ\right) \amp \cos\left(-45^\circ\right) \end{bmatrix}</md>. Therefore, multiplication by <m>P</m> rotates vectors <m>45^\circ</m> clockwise.
            </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Combining parts (b) - (d) above, give a geometric description of what multiplication by <m>A</m> does to an arbitrary vector <m>\vec x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Mutliplcation by <m>A</m> does the following:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, it rotates the vector <m>45^\circ</m> counterclockwise.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Then, scales the resulting vector by <m>4</m> in the <m>x_1</m>-direction and by <m>2</m> in the <m>x_2</m>-direction.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Finally, rotates the resulting vector <m>45^\circ</m> clockwise.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-4-singular-values">
    <title>Singular Values</title>

    <p>
        Recall from <xref ref="thm-orthogonal-maps"/> that multiplication by an orthogonal matrix does not change the angles between vectors nor the vector's length. Therefore, if <m>U</m> is an orthogonal matrix, we have that the linear transformation <m>T(\vec x) = U\vec x</m> must simply be a rotation and/or reflection. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Note that multiplication by a <m>m \times n</m> diagonal matrix <m>\Sigma</m> changes the vector from being in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to being in <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>, and then scales it along the appropriate coordinate axes.
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore, in general, we can use the SVD of a matrix <m>A</m> to describe how the linear transformation <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x</m> acts on the vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
    </p>
    <image xml:id="img-7-4-svd-structure" source="./Singular-Value-Decomposition-Transformation.png" width="70%" workspace="true">
      <shortdescription>Visualization of the SVD expressing a matrix as rotations and scalings.</shortdescription>
    </image>

    <p><nbsp/></p>


    </page>

    <page>

    <note>
        <title>Algorithm for Finding the SVD of <m>A</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                How do we find the SVD of a matrix <m>A</m>? 
                <ol marker="(1)">
                    <li workspace="2in">
                        <p>
                            Start by forming the symmetric matrix <m>A^TA</m> and finding its eigenvalues <m>\lambda_i</m>, with the eigenvalues assigned in <em>nonincreasing</em> order. Set <m>\sigma_i = \sqrt{\lambda_i}</m>. These are the <term>singular values</term> of <m>A</m> and they are the entries on the diagonal of <m>\Sigma</m>. Fill any missing diagonal elements with 0.
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Since <m>A^TA</m> is symmetric, we know from <xref ref="thm-spectral"/> that it has <m>n</m> real eigenvalues. A bonus fact is that for symmetric matrices of the form <m>A^TA</m>, the <m>n</m> eigenvalues must be nonnegative, so <md>\lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \ge \cdots \ge \lambda_n \ge 0.</md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    
                    <li workspace="2in">
                        <p>
                            Next, find <m>n</m> <em>normalized</em> and <em>orthogonal</em> eigenvectors of <m>A^TA</m> and call them <m>\vec v_i</m>, with <m>\vec v_i</m> corresponding to eigenvalue <m>\lambda_i</m>. These vectors form the <em>rows</em> of <m>V^T</m>.
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Make sure to find enough orthonormal eigenvectors for each repeated eigenvalue, which we know we can do by <xref ref="thm-spectral"/>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Alternatively, we can think of the <m>\vec v_i</m> as the columns of <m>V</m>, but since SVD uses <m>V^T</m>, it is usually easier to think with respect to <m>V^T</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    
                    <li workspace="2in">
                        <p>
                            Use the formula <md>\vec u_i = \dfrac{1}{\sigma_i}A\vec v_i</md> to find the columns of <m>U</m>. If the rank of <m>A</m> is less than <m>m</m>, then this formula will not produce enough columns to fill <m>U</m>. We must find the remaining columns by extending the set <m>\left\{\vec u_1, \dots, \vec u_r\right\}</m> to an orthonormal basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The calculated vectors <m>\vec u_i</m> will be normalized and orthogonal to one another as long as the original <m>\vec v_i</m> were.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If the rank of <m>A</m> is less than <m>n</m>, then some of the eigenvalues found in (1) will be 0, which results in singular values of 0. These singular values can <em>not</em> be used in the formula, since that would result in dividing by 0. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        
    </note>
    
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-4-examples">
    <title>Examples</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-7-4-example1" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Construct the SVD of</p>
        <md>
          A = \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}.
        </md>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            First, we calculate the symmetric matrix <m>A^TA</m>. Note that <md>A^TA = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 8 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 24 \\ 24 \amp 73\end{bmatrix}</md>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, we find the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>. Note that <md>\det(A^TA - \lambda I) = (9-\lambda)(73-\lambda) - 24^2 = (\lambda - 81)(\lambda - 1)</md>. Therefore, the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m> are <m>\lambda_1 = 81</m> and <m>\lambda_2 = 1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, we find the singular values of <m>A</m> which are the square roots of the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m>. Therefore, we have that <md>\sigma_1 = \sqrt{\lambda_1} = 9</md> and <md>\sigma_2 = \sqrt{\lambda_2} = 1</md>. It follows that <md>\Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \sigma_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</md>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, we find corresponding eigenvectors for each eigenvalue of <m>A^TA</m>. Note that <md>A^TA - 81I = \begin{bmatrix} -72 \amp 24 \\ 24 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Thus, <md>\vec v_1 = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</md> is a unit eigenvector of <m>A^TA</m> corresponding to <m>\lambda_1 = 81</m>. Also, note that <md>A^TA - I = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 24 \\ 24 \amp 72 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</md>. It follows that <md>\vec v_2 = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</md> is a unit eigenvector of <m>A^TA</m> corresponding to <m>\lambda_2 = 1</m>. (Note that we could have found <m>\vec v_2</m> in an alternative way by using <xref ref="thm-orth-eigenspaces"/>.) These eigenvectors are the rows of <m>V^T</m>. Therefore, we have that <md>V^T = \begin{bmatrix} \vec v_1^T \\ \vec v_2^T \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \amp \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}} \\ \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}} \amp \frac{-1}{\sqrt{10}}\end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</md>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Lastly, we find the columns of <m>U</m> by using the formula <md>\vec u_i = \dfrac{1}{\sigma_i}A\vec v_i</md>. Note that <md>\vec u_1 = \frac{1}{\sigma_1}A\vec v_1 = \frac{1}{9}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{9\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 27 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</md> and <md>\vec u_2 = \frac{1}{\sigma_2}A\vec v_2 = \frac{1}{1}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Therefore, we have that <md>U = \begin{bmatrix} \vec u_1 \amp \vec u_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \amp -\frac{3}{\sqrt{10}}\end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}</md>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We can check our Singular Value Decomposition by verifying that the matrices <m>U, \Sigma,</m> and <m>V^T</m> have the appropriate properties and satisfy <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m>. Note that <md>
                <mrow>U\Sigma V^T \amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{10}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 27 \\ 3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{10}\begin{bmatrix}30 \amp 80 \\ 0 \amp 30 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} = A</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
    </page>

    <page>
    <example xml:id="ex-7-4-example2" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Construct the SVD of</p>
        <md>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp -1\\ -2 \amp 2\\ 2 \amp -2\end{bmatrix}.
        </md>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            First, note that <md>A^TA = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \\ -1 \amp 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp -9 \\ -9 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix}</md>. We have that <md>\det(A^TA - \lambda I) = (9-\lambda)^2 - 81 = \lambda^2 - 18\lambda = \lambda(\lambda - 18)</md>. So, the eigenvalues of <m>A^TA</m> are <m>\lambda_1 = 18</m> and <m>\lambda_2 = 0</m>. It follows that the singular values of <m>A</m> are <m>\sigma_1 = \sqrt{18} = 3\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>\sigma_2 = 0</m>. Recall that <m>\Sigma</m> has the same dimensions as <m>A</m>. Thus, <md>\Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} 3\sqrt{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Since there is only one nonzero singular value, we have that the rank of <m>A</m> is 1.
        </p>
        <p>
            Note that <md>A^TA - 18 I = \begin{bmatrix} -9 \amp -9 \\ -9 \amp -9 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Therefore, <md>\vec v_1 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</md> is a unit eigenvector of <m>A^TA</m> corresponding to an eigenvalue of <m>\lambda_1 = 18</m>. Also, note that <md>A^TA - 0I = \begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp -9 \\-9 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Therefore, <md>\vec v_2 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</md> is a unit eigenvector of <m>A^TA</m> corresponding to an eigenvalue of <m>\lambda_2 = 0</m>. it follows that <md>V^T = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</md>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We can find <m>\vec u_1</m> using the formula since <m>\sigma_1 \neq 0</m>. Note that <md>\vec u_1 = \frac{1}{\sigma_1}A\vec v_1 = \frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{6}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Note that we cannot use the formula to find <m>\vec u_2</m> since that would require us to divide by <m>\sigma_2 = 0</m>. However, we can find <m>\vec u_2</m> by using the properties of <m>U</m>. Recall <m>U</m> is a <m>3 \times 3</m> <em>orthogonal</em> matrix. So, we actually need to find <em>two</em> more columns of <m>U</m>. Thankfully, we can choose any two unit vectors as long as they make <m>U</m> an orthogonal matrix.
        </p> 
        <p> One set of vectors could be <md>\vec u_2 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad \vec u_3 = \frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</md>. Let's check that the matrix with these columns, call it <m>U_1</m>, works. Note that <md>
            <mrow>U_1\Sigma V^T\amp = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{3\sqrt{2}} \\ -\frac{2}{3} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{2}{3} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3\sqrt{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{3} \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{3\sqrt{2}} \\ -\frac{2}{3} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{2}{3} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{3\sqrt{2}} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} = A</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            The previous choice of <m>\vec u_2</m> and <m>\vec u_3</m> are not the only vectors that could fill the columns of <m>U</m>. Suppose instead we chose <md>\vec u_2' = \frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad \vec u_3' = \frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</md> as the columns of <m>U</m>, call the matrix <m>U_2</m>. Then, we also have that <m>A = U_2\Sigma V^T</m> is a valid Singular Value Decomposition of <m>A</m>. There are many valid factorizations when there is more than one missing column of <m>U</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-4-applications">
    <title>Applications of the SVD</title>
    <p>
        The SVD has been applied to many modern applications in CS, engineering, and mathematics. Some applications are:
    <ul>
      <li>Constructing bases for the four fundamental subspaces</li>
      <li>Forming approximations of a matrix</li>
      <li>Estimating the rank and the condition number of a matrix</li>
      <li>Computing the pseudoinverse of a matrix</li>
      <li>Linear least-squares problems</li> 
      <li>Non-linear least-squares problems</li> 
      <li>Image compression</li>
      <li>Machine learning and data mining</li>
      <li>Facial Recognition</li> 
      <li>Principal component analysis</li>
    </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
        Students are expected to be familiar with the first two items. We will explore these two items below.
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

</page>

<page>

    <p>
        Let <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix with rank <m>r</m>.
    </p>
    <p> 
        Consider the columns of <m>U</m>:
        <ul workspace="2in">
            <li>
                <p>
                    Recall that the formula for calculating the first few columns of <m>U</m> is <md>\vec u_i = \dfrac{1}{\sigma_i}A\vec v_i</md>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    It follows that <m>\left\{\vec u_1, \dots, \vec u_r\right\}</m> is a set of <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m> vectors that all live in <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal; <m>\Col(A)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the first <m>r</m> columns of <m>U</m> form an <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> for <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal basis; <m>\Col(A)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since the remaining columns of <m>U</m> are created so that all columns of <m>U</m> form an orthonormal basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>, we see that <m>\left\{\vec u_{r+1}, \dots, \vec u_m\right\}</m> is a set of <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m> vectors which live in <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal; <m>\Col(A)^\perp = \Nul(A^T)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the last <m>m - r</m> columns of <m>U</m> form an <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> for <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal basis; <m>\Nul(A^T)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
        </ul> 
        Now, consider the rows of <m>V^T</m>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The last <m>n-r</m> rows of <m>V^T</m> are eigenvectors of <m>A^TA</m> which correspond to an eigenvalue of <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>\lambda = 0</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>\left\{\vec v_{r+1}, \dots, \vec v_n\right\}</m> form an <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> for <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal basis; <m>\Nul(A^TA)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We have that <m>\Nul(A^TA) = \Nul(A)</m>. Thus, the last <m>n - r</m> rows of <m>V^T</m> form an <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> for <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal basis; <m>\Nul(A)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since <m>V^T</m> is an orthogonal matrix, we know that it's <m>n</m> rows form an orthonormal basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. Therefore, <m>\left\{\vec v_1, \dots, \vec v_r\right\}</m> is a set of <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m> vectors which live in <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal; <m>\Nul(A)^\perp = \Row(A)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    It follows that the first <m>r</m> rows of <m>V^T</m> form an <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> for <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                </p>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        orthonormal basis; <m>\Row(A)</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
</page>

<page>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-SVD-ortho-subspaces">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix with rank <m>r</m> and with SVD <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m>, where <md>U = \begin{bmatrix} \vec u_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec u_m \end{bmatrix}, \quad \Sigma = \begin{bmatrix}  \sigma_1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp \sigma_2 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\ \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp \sigma_r \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad V^T = \begin{bmatrix} \vec v_1^T \\ \vdots \\ \vec v_n^T \end{bmatrix}</md>  Then,
                <ol marker="(1)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\vec v_i = \sigma_i \vec u_i</m> for <m>i = 1, \cdots, r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\vec v_1, \dots, \vec v_r\right\}</m> is an orthonormal basis for <m>\Row(A)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\vec u_1, \dots, \vec u_r\right\}</m> is an orthonormal basis for <m>\Col(A)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\vec v_{r+1}, \dots, \vec v_n\right\}</m> is an orthonormal basis for <m>\Nul(A)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\vec u_{r+1}, \dots, \vec u_m\right\}</m> is an orthonormal basis for <m>\Nul(A^T)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image source="./4subspaces.jpg" width="100%">
                <shortdescription>A graphic depicting the relationship between the rows of V transpose and the columns of U.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
</page>

<page>

    <example workspace="true">
        <statement> 
            <p> 
                Let <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m> for <md>U = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \sqrt{5} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad V^T = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \sqrt{0.2} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \sqrt{0.8} \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ -\sqrt{0.8} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \sqrt{0.2} \end{bmatrix}</md>. Find an orthonormal basis for each of the four subspaces.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since <m>\Sigma</m> has three nonzero elements on its diagonal, we know that <m>\rank(A) = 3</m>. Therefore, the first 3 columns of <m>U</m> form an orthonormal basis for <m>\Col(A)</m> and the remaining column of <m>U</m> forms an orthonormal basis for <m>\Nul(A)^T</m>. Similarly, the first 3 rows of <m>V^T</m> form an orthonormal basis for <m>\Row(A)</m> and the remaining rows of <m>V^T</m> form an orthonormal basis for <m>\Nul(A)</m>. Therefore, we have that <md>
                    <mrow> \mathcal{B}_1 \amp = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right\} \text{ is an orthonormal basis for $\Col(A)$.}</mrow> 
                    <mrow> \mathcal{B}_2 \amp = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ -1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right\} \text{ is an orthonormal basis for $\Nul(A^T)$.}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \mathcal{B}_3 \amp = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{0.2} \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ \sqrt{0.8} \end{bmatrix}\right\} \text{ is an orthonormal basis for $\Row(A)$.}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \mathcal{B}_4 \amp = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} -\sqrt{0.8} \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ \sqrt{0.2} \end{bmatrix}\right\} \text{ is an orthonormal basis for $\Nul(A)$.}</mrow>  
                </md> 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  

  <page xml:id="p-7-4-spectral-connection">
    <title>SVD and Spectral Decomposition</title>

    <p>We can create the <term>spectral decomposition</term> for a general matrix <m>A</m> in a similar way to <xref ref="thm-spectral-decomposition"/>. </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-">
        <statement>
            <p>
                 Let <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m> be the SVD of a rank <m>r</m> matrix, with the columns of <m>U</m> given by <m>\vec u_i</m>, the entries on the diagonal of <m>\Sigma</m> given by <m>\sigma_i</m>, and the rows of <m>V^T</m> given by <m>\vec v_i</m>. Then, the <term>spectral decomposition</term> of <m>A</m> is given by 
    <md>
      A=\sum_{i=1}^r \sigma_i\,\vec u_i\vec v_i^T.
    </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example>
        <statement workspace="true">
            <p>
                Find the spectral decomposition of <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Use the decomposition to identify the best rank 1 approximation of <m>A</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Using the information from the solution to <xref ref="ex-7-4-example1"/>,we have that <md>
                    <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \amp = \sigma_1\vec u_1 \vec v_1^T + \sigma_2 \vec u_2 \vec v_2^T</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = (9)\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} + (1)\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{9}{10}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 9 \\1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} + \frac{1}{10}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -9 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2.7 \amp 8.1 \\ 0.9 \amp 2.7 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0.3 \amp -0.1 \\ -0.9 \amp 0.3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>.
                Therefore, the best rank 1 matrix that approximates <m>A</m> is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2.7 \amp 8.1 \\ 0.9 \amp 2.7 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
    
  </page>

  <page>
    <p>
        We end this section, and this course, by investigating the connection between Spectral Decomposition and Image Compression. Consider an image in grayscale consisting of pixels in a <m>880 \times 1100</m> grid. Since each pixel is in grayscale, we can assign it an integer value between 0 and 255 depending on how gray it is, where 0 is black and 255 is white. We can form a <m>880 \times 1100</m> matrix where each entry is the grayscale value of the associated pixel. In general, the rank of this matrix could be quite high. 
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, suppose we have selected an image and created the associated matrix and it has rank <m>776</m>. One way to store this image in a slightly compressed manner is to store the <m>776</m> basis vectors for <m>\Col(A)</m>, and then store a list of linear combinations describing how to use these <m>776</m> vectors to recreate all <m>880</m> columns (the dimensions of an image are reversed, first horizontal, then vertical).
    </p>
    <question workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Could we compress the file size further? Suppose we were okay with a little error in our image. Perhaps just a hair of fuzziness that could be corrected open reopening the compressed file. How could we go about doing this?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </question>
        
  </page>

  <page>
    <p>
        The idea is to find a good enough approximation of the image. We can use Spectral Decomposition to find the best rank <m>j</m> approximation for <m>j = 1, \dots, r</m>. We can save tons of storage by letting <m>j</m> be small, but then our image will be super blurry. We can have a very accurate image by letting <m>j</m> be large, but then the compression's filesize is not much smaller than the original's filesize. We need to find a <m>j</m> which balances these, a good approximation with small filesize.
    </p>
    <p>
        Here is the best rank 1 approximation for the image. Can you tell what the image is? 
        <image source="./buzz/rank_1.png" workspace="5in" width="70%">
            <shortdescription>Rank 1 approximation of image.</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </p>

    <p>
        Proceed through the next few images slowly so as not to spoil the surprise.
    </p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <p>
        Here is the best rank 2 approximation for the image. Can you tell what the image is?
        <image source="./buzz/rank_2.png" workspace="5in" width="70%">
            <shortdescription>Rank 2 approximation of image.</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <p>
        Here is the best rank 4 approximation for the image. Can you tell what the image is?
        <image source="./buzz/rank_4.png" workspace="5in" width="70%">
            <shortdescription>Rank 4 approximation of image.</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <p>
        Here is the best rank 8 approximation for the image. Can you tell what the image is?
        <image source="./buzz/rank_8.png" workspace="5in" width="70%">
            <shortdescription>Rank 8 approximation of image.</shortdescription>
        </image>
    </p>
  </page>

